Salute and respect to the brave PAF pilot, Kamran Bashir.

Our heartfelt prayers are with his parents, regardless of their religious background.

As a society, we tend to admire heroes when they succeed‚Äîstanding beside them in moments of glory. Yet, when they face challenges, true support is often lacking. This tendency exists among both Muslims and non-Muslims, though, regrettably, it is sometimes more pronounced towards non-Muslimism. The story and struggles of javelin athlete and Olympic gold medalist Arshad Nadeem are a good example of this tendency.

If we truly follow the teachings of the Quran and the Sunnah, we must uphold the dignity and rights of people from all religions on merit. Sadly, as a Pakistani and a Muslim, I acknowledge with a heavy heart that there are extremist elements within our society who exploit religious divisions for political gain. This is wrong and must be condemned and stopped at every level.

Time will tell whether this pilot‚ÄîKamran Bashir‚Äîwill rise through the ranks on merit to become an Air Vice Marshal or Air Marshal. When that time comes, it will reflect not only on his abilities but also on the fairness and inclusiveness of our institutions and society.

text:
There was a PAF flight officer named Mervyn Leslie Middlecoat. He fought in the 1965 conflict with India. During the 1967 Arab - Israeli war, he formed part of a contingent of Pakistani pilots who volunteered to fly for the participating Arab states. Mervyn was sent to Jordan. Later on, Middlecoat was KIA during the 1971 war. 
Incidently, the legendary Saif ul Azam flew for both Iraq and Jordan. He was credited with shooting down 4 Israeli jets in total. During 1965, he had shot down at least 1 indian aeroplane. Sadly, due to being of Bengali origin, Saif ul Azam was not permitted to fight during the tragic 1971 war. Soon after, he went to the new state of Bangladesh, where he held prominent and senior positions in both military and civil aviation. He died in Dhaka in 2020, mourned by many, including numerous senior PAF officers. 
Another PAF pilot of Bengali origin, M.M Alam, became an extremely rare 'Ace in a day' when he shot down FIVE indian planes in a couple of minutes during the 1965 war. Again, ashamedly, Alam, due to being of Bengali heritage, was denied permission to fly during the 1971 war. First of all, this was never about blind nationalism ‚Äî it's about truth and accountability. Let's assume for a moment that everything the Indian government says is accurate. But have you heard what External Affairs Minister Jaishankar reportedly said? That we informed Pakistan one hour before launching a strike, making it clear our target was terrorists, not the army.

Seriously? We warned the so-called enemy in advance? And we expected the terrorists to stay put and wait for missiles to fall on them? Who are we trying to fool ‚Äî the world, or ourselves?

And then we‚Äôre told we destroyed 11 Pakistani airbases. Yet somehow, they still managed to scramble jets the same night, take down six of our aircraft, and even kill one pilot while injuring two others. Is this what we‚Äôre calling a 'great victory'?

Check international media ‚Äî Reuters, Le Monde, The Economist, The Diplomat, The Telegraph, even France 24 (yes, the same France that sold us Rafales) ‚Äî many are reporting the actual losses we suffered. Meanwhile, the Indian Air Force refuses to release a detailed account of what really happened. Why? What are they hiding?

And when diplomats like Vikram Misri merely announce a ceasefire, they face threats and abuse. Is this the new India ‚Äî where truth is treason, and blind loyalty is the only accepted narrative?

Let‚Äôs be honest ‚Äî we‚Äôve failed diplomatically, militarily, and morally. The rest of the world is watching us descend into the same extremist trap we once condemned. If we keep silencing dissent, rewriting facts, and weaponizing religion, we won't need enemies. Bharatis üáÆüá≥ always make this false claim and it is not true. 

The non-Muslim pop. of present day Pakistan (West Pakistan until 1971) has in fact  grown and not declined. 

It was the eastern wing or East Pakistan which  became Bangladesh in 1971 that had a sizeable non-Muslim population. So when East Pakistan left in 1971, that naturally reduced the figure of non Muslims in Pakistan. 

Present day Pakistan or   West Pakistan until 1971, was always predominantly Muslim since Islam arrived there  in the 8th century. 

This is unsurprising considering its geog location in South-Central Asia. Almost the entire swathe from Pakistan to Central Asia, all the way to Turkey, Central Asian republics,  the Caucasus to  Bosnia and Albania, to West Asia and North Africa, to much of West Africa, the Horn of Africa and much of East Africa, is almost entirely Muslim. This is the 'heartland of the Islamic world'  and it is one land mass.

Whilst Pakistan and its people are not imperfect  and have flaws, generally speaking most people are fairly tolerant and don't bother religious minorities. The Quran clearly states "there is no compulsion in religion".

So Allah said about that: 'And on that day, the believers will rejoice - with the help of Allah. He helps whom He wills, and He is the Almighty, the Most Merciful (30:4 & 5). The Quraish wanted the Persians to be victorious since they were not people of the Book, nor did they believe in the Resurrection. So when Allah revealed these Ayat, Abu Bakr As-Siddiq, may Allah be pleased with him, went out, proclaiming throughout Makkah: 'Alif Lam Mim. The Romans have been defeated. In the nearest land, and they, after their defeat, will be victorious, in Bid' years (30:1-4).' Some of the Quraish said: 'Then this is (a bet) between us and you. Your companion claims that the Romans will defeat the Persians in Bid' years, so why have have a bet on that between us and you?' Abu Bakr said: 'Yes.' This was before betting has been forbidden. So Abu Bakr and the idolaters made a bet, and they said to Abu Bakr: 'What do you think - Bid' means something between three and nine years, so let us agree on the middle.' So they agreed on six years; Then six years passed without the Romans being victorious. The idolaters took what they won in the bet from Abu Bakr. When the seventh year came and the Romans were finally victorious over the Persians, the Muslims rebuked Abu Bakr for agreeing to six years. He said: 'Because Allah said: 'In Bid' years.' At that time, many people became Muslims."

Reference	                 : Jami` at-Tirmidhi 3194
In-book reference	         : Book 47, Hadith 246
English translation	 : Vol. 5, Book 44, Hadith 3194

text:
The was a PAF flight officer named Mervyn Leslie Middlecoat. He fought in the 1965 conflict with India. During the 1967 Arab - Israeli war he formed part of a  contingent of Pakistani pilots who volunteered to fly for the participating Arab states. Mervyn was sent to Jordan. Later on Middlecoat was KIA during the 1971 war.

Incidently, the legendary Saif ul Azam, flew for both Iraq and also Jordan. He was credited with shooting down 4 Israeli jets, in total. During the 1965 he had shot down at least 1 indian aeroplane. Sadly, due to being of Bengali origin, Saif ul Azam was not permitted to fight during the tragic 1971 war. Soon after he went to the new state of Bangladesh, where he held prominent and senior positions in both military and civil aviation. He died in Dhaka in 2020, mourned by many, including numerous senior PAF officers.

Another PAF pilot of Bengali origin, M.M Alam became an extremely rare 'Ace in a day' when he shot down FIVE indian planes in a couple of minutes during the 1965 war. Again, ashamedly, Alam, due to being of Bengali heritage was denied permission to fly during the 1971 war. 'Little Dragon' as he was affectionately known, remained loyal to Pakistan, living in Karachi until his death in 2013.

He was one of forty five Polish officers and airmen who joined RPAF on contract in the early 1950s. After completion of his initial contract, Turowicz opted to stay on in Pakistan and continued to serve in the Pakistan Air Force. Turowicz was the administrator of Pakistan's Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO) from 1967 to 1970.
Turowicz made significant contributions to Pakistan's missile/rocket program as a chief aeronautical engineer. In Pakistan, he remains highly respected as a scientist and noted aeronautical engineer. He and his family never left Pakistan
